President Trump's tax reform has resulted in various companies offering bonuses and benefits to their employees. Anthem, an insurance giant, announced that it will contribute more than $58 million to employees' retirement accounts. Lowe's plans to pay one-time bonuses of up to $1,000 and expand benefits packages for its hourly employees. Best Buy will give bonuses of $1,000 to full-time workers and $500 to part-time employees. Tyson Foods will give $1,000 and $500 bonuses to eligible employees. Hostess Brands will provide workers with $1,250 in cash and one year of free snacks. CVS Health will increase employee pay and introduce paid parental leave. Chipotle will offer one-time bonuses of between $250 and $1,000, as well as expanded training programs and parental leave. Charter Communications has set its minimum wage at $15 an hour. Leak Sealers, a female-owned engineering company, is also giving out bonuses to its employees. BP will increase its investment in the United States after the tax reform. Boeing has announced changes to its volunteer and gift match programs and has allocated $100 million towards corporate charitable investments.